2. Is calcium the only nutrient needed for bone health
and prevention of osteoperosis?

NO!!! The first thing you must realize is that bone is
living tissue. Bone is more than a collection of calcium
crystals. It is continually remodeling itself and constantly
going through a wide range of biochemical reactions.
Bone tissue is made up of not only bone cell, but an
intercellular matrix. Because of these factors calcium is
just not enough to maintain the health of bone tissue or
prevent osteoporosis. Research is showing that numerous
nutritional factors are required to keep bones healthy.
They include: calcium, magnesium, manganese, boron,
zinc, strontium, copper, silicon, Vitamin K, D, C, B6,
and there may be more. So, calcium may be important
but it's not the whole story. Supplementation is also
only part of the answer, diet in general is very important.
Too much sugar, caffeine, protein, salt, and alcohol may
put you at a higher risk for osteoporosis. Exercise is
another factor that must be utilized to maintain healthy
bones.

